5000|$|Long-term {{prospects}} for the growth and stabilization of the markets for vanilla and <b>ylang-ylang</b> did not appear strong in the early 1990s. Vanilla faced increased competition from synthetic flavorings, and the preferences of perfume users were {{moving away from the}} sweet fragrance provided by <b>ylang-ylang</b> essence. Copra, the dried coconut meat that yields coconut oil, once an important Comoran export, had ceased to be a significant factor in the economy by the late 1980s, when the world's tastes shifted from high-fat coconut oil toward [...] "leaner" [...] substances such as palm oil. Although clove production and revenues also experienced swings, in the early 1990s cloves did not appear to face the same sorts of challenges confronting vanilla and <b>ylang-ylang.</b> Most Comoran vanilla is grown on Njazidja; Nzwani is the source of most ylangylang.|$|E
50|$|The {{essential}} oil {{is used in}} aromatherapy. It is believed to relieve high blood pressure, normalize sebum secretion for skin problems, and {{is considered to be}} an aphrodisiac. According to Margaret Mead, it was used as such by South Pacific natives such as the Samoan Islanders where she did much of her research. The oil from <b>ylang-ylang</b> is widely used in perfumery for oriental or floral themed perfumes (such as Chanel No. 5). <b>Ylang-ylang</b> blends well with most floral, fruit and wood scents.|$|E
